<TITLE> 10-truck arms case gets 4th probe extension </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Chittagong, July 22 (bdnews24.com)  A Chittagong court has ordered a 75-day extension of investigations into the infamous 2004 '10-truck' arms haul, the fourth such extension in the case. The third time extension for investigators in the case ended Wednesday "Chittagong session's judge Bhabani Prashad Singh extended the probe period up to October 5," public prosecutor Kamal Uddin told bdnews24.com. Investigation officer Moniruzzaman Chowdhury appealed to the court on July 13, seeking a 90-day extension said Kamal. Chowdhury told the judge investigators needed more time as they had still to discover the top dealers involved in the arms consignment, the transporting ship and all those who were present during the offloading of the consignment at a Chittagong port. Police seized the 10 trucks of arms and ammunition as they were being offloaded at the the Chittagong Urea Fertiliser Ltd jetty on Apr 2, 2004. Four top former officers of the National Security Intelligence agency, including two former NSI heads, and the truck owners have been arrested and held for questioning over recent months, since new investigators were appointed and the long-stalled case was set in motion again in January this year. b
